{"/service/ndnp/curiv/batch_curiv_archylee_ver01/data/sn82016196/00516992438/1949012001/0062.xml":{"full_text":"Youth Activities Throughout the Nation\n\u2014The California Eagle, Thursday, January 20, 1949\n18\nKINLOCH'S\nKORNER\nDedicated to the memory of John\nKinloch, who died in the etruggle\nto dettroy Faeciem\nRaisin' Cain\nBy CARL L. CAIN\nOn the second of November\nonce every four years the peo\nple of the United States hand\nthe President-to-be their votes.\nThat future President is the boss\nturkey of either the Democratic\nor Republican Parties. It ap\npears that the modern trend of\nthinking is that anyone not a\nmember of the two parties is a\ncommunist, rabble-rouser, dicta\ntor\u2014or all three.\nMeanwhile the two boss tur\nkeys strut proudly about, boast-\ning of what their young turkeys\nwill be like when they are\nhatched by Congress during the\nimmediately following four\nyears.\nThey also promise\u2014though in i\nno boisterous manner not to\ngive any choice sections of the\nfresh young birds certain ones\nwill be eating, to anyone <who\ndid not help out with the cam-\npaign; and the reverse to those\nwho did toil. That might explain\nwhy some rather rancid foxes\nare going to have fresh young\nturkey for dinner quite often 1\nduring the next four years.\nThen on January 20, of the i\nnext year, we have what is\nknown as Inauguration Day. i\nThe four-year meal has been i\npaid for and the dispute over 1\nthe leadership chair has been\nsettled; so we give the man of\nthe people's choice these two\nitems and send him on his way.\nWe do so with a huge parade\nin Washington District of Co- 1\nlumbia. (Here the people do not i\nvote, so no one could have voted\nagainst the President \u2014of that\nhe can be certain as he traverses\ndown the seven and one-half\nmile course of the parade.)\nHe rides happily along, amidst\nthe sound of hoofing horses and\nbuggies' wheels on the concrete\n\u2014shows how proud we are of our\nmodern scientific means of travel\nand life in general.\nBut it is truly a great occa\nsion; on that most people will\nagree. It is like the hand that\ntests the pulse-beat of the na\ntion. On that day people are\nhappy, and should feel that it\nis their day\u2014for on election day\nthey decided who would be rid\ning in that buggy.\nPublic School Adult' Education\nEnrollment Open For Spring\nThe spring term of classes for\nadults offered by the Los Angeles\nPublic Schools in East Los An\ngeles open on January 31. A\ngreat many inquiries have al\nready been made at the three\nlocations which are open in the\nevening.\nAt the Belvedere Junior High\nSchool, located at 320 North\nRecord Street, classes are of\nfered on Monday and Wednes\nday evenings in English, Citi\nzenship, and Woodshop.\nAt the Garfield High School\nlocation, 5105 East Sixth Street,\nclasses are held on Tuesday and\nThursday evenings.\nThe classes are Art Craft,\nElectric for Apprentices, Eng\nlish, Badminton, Sheet Metal\nfor Apprentices, Shorthand,\nDR. GAY\nCREDIT DENTIST\nTHE FAMILY CREDIT DENTIST\nOPEN EVENINGS\n20th Anniversary\nNO APPOINTMENT NECESSARY\nDental Plates\nOne Day Plate Service\nImmediate Restorations\nExtration of Teeth and Mouth Preparation for Partials\nand Full Dentures\nPartial Dentures and Removable Bridgework\nPlates Repaired While You Wait\nEASY CREDIT\nALWAYS LOW PRICES\nNew Hours 9 A.M. to 9 P.M.\nDR. GAY, Credit Dentist\nCORNER VERNON and CENTRAL AVE.\nCE. 2-1397\nWhat most people are unable\nto understand, however, is why\nthe newspaper reporters and col\numnists (be there an essential\ndifference) try so hard to work\nup steam and fervor about the\nInauguration, as about every\nthing else that takes place now.\nBut it is becoming tradition\nally American\u2014and regretfully\ntoo\u2014to make \"much ado about\nnothing.\"\nWho cares about the Missouri\nmules to be used in the parade?\nWhat makes the mules more val\nuable now than they were the\nday before the parade or worth\nmore than the day after the pa\nrade? There are a hundred other\nsuch points of interest.\nI call it sensationalism, al\nthough certain OTHER aspects\nof it is downright slander. Some\nof our radio commentators have\nbeen stung hard by the slander\nthose melodic voices from which\nthe venom pours.\nMany of us were carried along\nby the tide of publicity had by\nthe great Inauguration Day. But\nothers expected the President's\nspeech to be a drab repetition\nof the things he had already\nsaid in his State of the Union\nmessage two weeks earlier. The\ntext was about twenty-five hun\ndred words\u2014less than one-third\nthe length of the actual Demo\ncratic platform, which was about\nseven thousand words long.\nObviously the only thing dif\nferent about the campaign prom\nises and the Inauguration Day\naddress is that Congress is stand\ning by, pen in hand, to fulfill\ntheir leader's magnicient wishes\nfor the manufacture of a better\nAmerica. Therefore, a certain\ncanount of constraint is natural.\nOther items in the news are\nthat a certain senator\u2014appar\nently caught in the \"wake of\nthe red witch\" had announced\nhis candidacy for the office of\nMayor of Los Angeles come the\nApril elections. Mayor Bow\nron will be in the race, too.\nPrices are going down and\nso is Rankin from the top man\nin the House of Un-American\nActivities.\nFootnote: Appearance\u2014the art\nof deception.\nTypewriting, Office Machines,\nDressmaking, and Upholstery.\nThe Roosevelt High School Cen\nter which is open five evenings\neach week offers classes in all\nfields of study. These include\nCommercial Bookkeeping. Type\nwriting, English, Arithmetic, and\nhigh school subjects. In the Vo\ncational Branch are Blue Print\nReading, Architectural Drafting,\nAuto Mechanics, Cabinet Making,\nCarpentry for Apprentices, Wood\nshop, Power Sewing, and Uphol\nstery.\nThe newer classes are Cera\nmics. Art and Metal Crafts, Citi\nzenship, and Driver Education.\nAcademic classes leading to a\nhigh school diploma include\nSpanish., Mathematics, History,\nEnglish, and Government.\nHoward University Students Receive Philip Morris Prizes\nAT the recent Fellowship Dance, Howard University students receive the radios and television sets awarded\ntheir fraternities and sororities by Philip Morris Co. for winning the Campus scorecasting contests\nby having the most accurate group score predictions during the football season. Left to right, Anita Moore,\nDelta Sigma Theta, second prize of an Admiral Radio Console: R. C. Redhead, Philip Morris on campus\nrepresentative; Ann Lee. Alpha Kappa Alpha, first prize of Admiral Television set; Herbert H. Wright,\ncollege representative for Philip Morris; Ernestine Hairston, Philip Morris on campus representative; and\nGeorge Elliot, Omega Psi Phi, third prize of an Admiral radio console set Individual prizes were also awarded\nto winning students.\nMISS VERSIA LINDSAY\nspellman College, Atlanta, rendered a solo, \"My Soul\u2019s Been\nAnchored In The Lord,\u201d at the recent Zeat Phi Beta sorority\nboule in Philadelphia. Seated on the platform behind the\nsiivger from left to right: Mrs. Lullelia W. Harrison, former\ngrand basileus; and honorary members, Mesdames Cecelia\nKing, wife of the Liberian Minister to the U. S., and Julia\nWest Hamilton, prominent Washington club woman.\nCommencement Week at ELAJC Beginning\nSun., Jan. 23. Class of 109 to Graduate\nDr. Alvin Haag, of the Univer\nsity of Redlands, will address 109\nEast Los Angeles junior college\ngraduates and their guests in\nbaccalaureate services at 3:30\nSunday afternoon, January 23,\nfollowed by commencement cere\nmonies at 10:30 a.m., Friday,\nt no J \u2019C\u00bb\nJanuary 28.\nBoth events will be held in\nthe arena theater. Included in\nthe semi-annual services will be\n\u0964a scripture and benediction read-\ning by the Rev. John Imbach.\narea youth worker of the Univer- j\nsity Religious Conference of\nSouthern California. The invoca\ntion will be delivered by Rabbi J\nAbraham N. Winoker, director of\nthe Los Angeles B'nai B\u2019rith.\nAt the graduation exercises,\nDr. Hugh M. Tiner, of Pepperdine\nCollege, will deliver theopening\naddress. Bruce A. Findlay, as\nsistant superintendent of Los I\nAngeles city schools, will confer\n30 The Broadway Federal Savings\nand Loan Association of\n0 Los Angeles\na THE FASTEST GROWING SAVINGS\nINSTITUTION IN THE WEST\nwllr lUriCni\nDividend Rate Join Our Christmas Club\nNow\nAll Accounts Opened Before the 11th of\nEach Month Eam as of the First\nFEDERALLY INSURED to SSOOO PER ACCOUNT\nAccounts Opened by Mail \u2014Write or Phone for Information\n\u201cListen to the Broadway Federal\u2019s Weekly Broadcast every Friday\n\u2022t 8:00 PM. over Station K.F.0.X., 1280 on your dial.\u201d\n4325-29 SO. BROADWAY AD. 3-7246\nLOS ANGELES, CALIFORNIA\nof Houston, Texas, voice student at\nthe regrees to the graduates.\n1 i Thirty-five awards will be pre\nsented to students who have\nbeen outstanding in scholastic\n1 work and service to the school in\nthe two years of college.\nThe Order of the Green Key is\ngranted ot students who have\ncarried 10% or more units of\niwork each semester and who\nhave maintained not less than a\ni 2.0 scholastic average, including\njoutstanding service to the col\nlege through leadership in one\nior more college activities not\nstrictly of a scholastic nature.\nThe Frank Carroll Merit award\niis presented semi-annually ot a\nman in the graduating class who\nis outsatnding in leaderdship,\ncitizenship, and scholarship.\nThe East Los Angeles Business\nand Professional Women's Club\naward is made semi-annually to j\na woman of the graduating class\nwho is outstanding in Associat-\nAll Milk Must\nBe Pasteurized\nThe City Council this week\nadopted an ordinance requiring\nall milk in the City of Los Ange\nles to be pasteurized or to be\ncertified raw milk.\nSponsored by Kenneth Hahn,\ncouncilman of the Bth District,\nthis ordinance received a unani\nmous vote. Hahn, who is chair\nman of the Public Health and\nWelfare Committee of the City\nCouncil, held hearings relative\nto the fact that 44,000 quarts of\nmilk were being sold daily in\nLos Angeles without any pas\nteurization or without being cer\ntified as to cleanliness as raw\nmilk.\nThe ordinance makes it com\npulsory that milk in the City of\nLos Angeles will either be pas\nteurized or be certified as to raw\nmil. This necessary health law\nwill prevent undulent fever,\ndiptheria an dother diseases.\nCouncilman Hahn said this is\na progressive mark forward in\nthe ever-battling fight against\ndiseases carried through milk\nsupplies.\nNAACP Youth\nMeet in April\nNEW YORK A call to the\nThird Annual Youth Legislative\nConference of the National Asso\nciation for the Advancement of\nColored People, to be held in\nWashington, April 20-23, was is\nsued last week jointly by Mrs.\nRuby Hurley, NAACP youth sec\nretary and the National Planning\nand Advisory Committee of\nNAACP youth councils and col\nlege chapters.\ned Students\u2019 activities, in service\nto the college, in social and ath\nletic activities, and in scholar\nship.\nCum Laude is graned to stu\ndents who have carried 1014 or\nmore units of work each semes\nter and who have maintained\nnot less than a B plus scholastic\naverage, including membership\nin the Junior College California\nHonor Society, Alpha Gamma\nSigma.\nWho ever you are and where ever you\u2019ve been there\u2019s only\none dude ranch you can take your kids and have fun on the\nweek end.\nWINTER RATES; Fri. nite, all day Sat. and Sun. for $12.00\neach and SB.OO for kids. Come early and get a private\nroom. All rooms are the same price.\nAT MURRAY\u2019S you have your private swimming pool, a\nprivate horse, and your meals served to you In bed If you\ndesire. No other place can make such a statement and live\nup to them. Come and see for yourself.\nMURRAY'S ES\u00a3 Dude Ranch\nPost Office Box 257, Victorville, California\nLeia O. Murray, Mgr.\nTEL. VICTORVILLE 5251\nRATES\nSINGLE, PER DAY 8:50\nCOUPLES. PER DAY 12.00\nSINGLE, WEEKLY RATE 35.00\nCOUPLE, WEEKLY RATE 65.00\nSEPARATE BEDS 70.00\nROOM WITH PRIVATE BATH\nSINGLE, PER DAY 7.50\nCOUPLE, PER DAY 14.00\nSINGLE, WEEKLY 40.00\nCOUPLE, WEEKLY 75.00\nSEPARATE BEDS 80.00\nCHILDREN\u2019S RATES\nCHILDREN\u2019S DAY RATES 4.00\nCHILDREN\u2019S WEEKLY BATES SO.OO\nTELEPHONE VICTORVILLE 5251\nDeposits must accompany all reaervatfona\nPlayground\nFacilities\nIncreased\nEn the southeast Los Angeles,\nWatts and West Jefferson areas,\na new playground site has been\npartially acquired at 35th street\nand Denker avenue; negotiations\nare under way for the purchase\nof a playground site in the\nWashington boulevard district\neast of Main street; additional\nland has been acquired to en\nlarge the Central Playground,\n1357 East 22nd street; and a new\nplayground site has been ac\nquired kt 89th street and Avalon\nboulevard.\nPlans are being drawn for\nplayground community club\nhouses at South Park Play\nground, at Ross Snyder Play\nground, and at the new 89th\nStreet and Avalon Playground.\nPlans are being prepared by ar\nchitects for a modern swimming\npool and bathhouse at South\nPark Playground.\nMiscellaneous improvements\ninclude resurfacing of ball dia\nmonds, new play apparatus, new\nbleachers, fencing, landscaping,\nand other features at many play\ngrounds.\nA new youth recreation center\nhas been established in Watts\nat 10125 South Beach street.\nAdult Students\nStudy Classes\nAny adult in the East Los An\ngeles area who has not complet\ned his high school education or\nwould like to improve his edu\ncational background may attend\nclasses being offered at the\nRoosevelt Evening High School\nCenter, which is open five eve\nnings each week at 450 S. Fick\nett st.\nCounselors are available at the\nGarfield High School location on\nTuesday evening and at the\nRoosevelt High School Monday\nthrough Thursday to assist .those\nwho wish to qualify for a high\nschool diploma, as well as adults\nwho wish to be advised in re\nlated educational problems.\nAdults wishing to enroll for\nhigh school subjects are urged\nto consult with the counselors\nimmediately in order to insure\nthemselves a place in the new\nclasses. The spring term begins\non January 31.\nArt Pictures\nMusuem Fare\nFive motion pictures most of\nthem dealing with the art, music\nand handicrafts of India will\nmake up the next documentary\nfilm program at the Los Angeles\nCounty Museum in Exposition\nPark on Friday, January 21 at 8\np.m.\nThe titles of the films are\n\u201cKashmir Story,\u201d \u201cHandicrafts of\nSouth India,\u201d \u201cBharatratyam,\u201d\n\u201cMelody of Hindustan,\u201d and \u201cOur\nHeritage.\u201d\nC.W.A. Parade in Long\nBeach Fri., Jan. 28\nChristian Willing Workers -As\nsociation is opening a Long\nBeach branch, and plans are well\nunderway for a \u201cGrand Opening\nand Election of Officers.\u201d Ac\ncording to the president, John F.\nRowe, a youth division will be\nset up, and a parade in Long\nBeach, January 28,1949, at 7 p.m.\nwill be the opening gun for a\nnew membership drive, and a\nyouth division celebration.\nCAPETOWN\u2014Henry Potts, a\nNegro who claims to be 100 years\nold, became the father of a son\ntoday. His wife is 39.\n28th Street Branch Observes\nWeek-Long, City-Wide Drive\nBeginning Sunday, January 23,\nthe 28th Street Branch Y.M.C.A.\nwill participate in a city-wide\nobservance of Y.M.C.A. Week in\nLos Angeles. The 22 branches\nof the \u201cY\u201d here will celebrate\nthe occasion through programs\nand special events.\nMayor Fletcher Bowron has is\nsued a proclamation stipulating\nthe week of January 23 to 30 as\nY.M.C.A. Week. \"In testimony to\nthe value of this splendid youth\nserving organization, I urge all\ncitizens to join with me in pay\ning honor and respect to the\nYoung Men\u2019s Christian Associa\ntion of Los Angeles.\u201d\nAs a part of this great week of\nrecognition of the work of the\nY.M.C.A., the Church Federation\nof Los Angeles has named Sun\nday, January 23, at Y.M.C.A. Sun\nday in the churches.\nMany churches in this commu\nnity will have special programs\nand speakers to bring the mes\nsage of the \u201cY\u201d to their congre\ngations.\nListed among the churches\nwhich are participating are:\nBaptist: Evening Star, Faithful\nCentral, Morning Star, Revela\ntion, Progressive Victory, South\nParkway, St. Marks. First Bap\nttist, ion Hill, St. Paul and Great\ner Cornerstone. Christian: Ava\nlon and Cosmopolitan.\nMethodist: Philips Temple,\nWesley Chapel, Second A.M.E.,\nWard Chapel, Bowen, Bethel and\nFirst A.M.E. Zion. Other churches\nare Lincoln Memorial Congrega-\nCONFIDENCE\nin your doctor is a prerequisite\nCONFIDENCE IN YOUR DRUGGIST\nIS RS IMPORTANT\nWe Bid For This Confidence\nDELIVERY SERVICE DAILY EXCEPT SUNDAY\n10:00 A.M. TO 10:00 P.M.\nI ^^Pbone CEntury 2-0464\nV FOX DRUG STORE\n4209 So. Central Ave. Loe Angeles, CaiiL\nIllg\nJFSe&tanp\n3>k GOOD IDEAS ^<l\nw\nA Mfc\nJL KITCHEN TRICK Lt\nOs LlFE\u2014use a dash of nutmeg\noy r CT am *d pota- J\nSa\u00dfl ,o or buttered L^wM\nbeans. A sprinkling of g\njQW caraway seeds adds\nsavor to pork roast a\nor spareribs. LgJ||\njZ HOUSEHOLD HINT.\nmJL CRUSHED NEWS- ^l'\nPAPERS are fine for Mllf\niE polishing mirrors and 31^^ a -C\nBKHI picture glass. Good EAB\nfor drying washed I\nwindows, too.\n^RECIPE^ R\nM PORTUGUESE ONION SOUP I\n^4 1\u00ab. \u00bblic\u00abd onion* tap. thy mo E*Wg\n1 dovo garlic, mincod 1 tap. calory tail\n6 bouillon cubo* 6 tlicot broad ff\nBB^I lightly browned. Add water, bouillon\ncubes, seasonings. Bring to boil, r'9\ns mmer 5 mins. Break eggs into sim- E.>^\nmering soup, cover and cook until E^W'\n^J|LJ e 99* ar Cut bread into quarters,\nW toast in />ven. Then place in soup\nbowls. Serve 1 egg to each portion S\nr TOAST OF THE TOWN.... I\nWEBER\u2019S TOAST, of course, gold W LJL\nmJHLJ within. It takes flavor-fresh Weber\u2019s M\nW i Bread to make such crunchingly good K\nI toast. Look for it in the blue and white I\nW checked gingham wrapper. W\nA WEE\nB 44-\u00bb I\n9* i 9F*9h w\ntional, Independent, Carver Mem\norial, Christ Temple Church of\nChrist and others.\nAll of the radio facilities of\nchurches and other agencies in\nthe community are giving air\ntime to observance of \"Y\u201d Week.\nTheaters in the community\nwill run a movie short about the\n\u201cY\u201d in observance of Y.M.C.A.\nWeek.\nChamber Diner\nHear Slitcher\nPrincipal speaker at the Los\nAngeles Chamber of Commerce\n1949 business outlook conference\nThursday at the Ambassador ho\ntel, will be Dr. Sumner H. Slitch\ner, professor of economics, Har\nvard university, it was an\nnounced by Chairman Paul S.\nArmstrong.\nThe economist is scheduled to\nappear at a dinner at 7 p.m.\nat which James E. Shelton, form\ner Chamber president, will pre\nside. Slitcher is to outline \u201cMan\nagement\u2019s Constant Challenge\nintegrating operations with eco\nnomic conditions.\u201d\nSlitcher, well known as an au\nthor, has served as arbitrator in\nmany labor disputes, is associate\nchairman of an advisory com\nmittee on the federal social se\ncurity program and is economist\nfor the committee for economic\ndevelopment and is chairman of\nits advisory board.","height":"30548","width":"22256"}}
